\fs30 G. Adamo\
\

\f1\b0\fs36 *My notes are in \cf2 red\cf0  
\f0\b\fs44 \

\fs36 \

\f1\b0 *\cf2 The four IC connections all have a causal and/or causal-like flavour. Therefore, an investigation of causation and causality within the literature is considered mandatory. The papers commented below are not the only ones available, yet they are the most relevant for developing an ontological theory of IC connections.
\f0\b \cf0 \
\
1. Background and main applied ontology literature
\f1\b0 \
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\cb3 \uc0\u8259 	}Galton, A. P. (2012). States, processes and events, and the ontology of causal relations.\cb1 \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Proposes an analysis of 
\f2\i causation
\f1\i0  (and not 
\f2\i causality
\f1\i0  - i.e. an explanatory law which holds between types) relationships between tokens of (i) \ul states\ulnone , (ii) \ul processes\ulnone , and (iii) \ul events\ulnone .\
\
Both \ul events\ulnone  and \ul states\ulnone  (conditions/preconditions*\cf2 here I see those as properties) \cf4 contribute to causation\cf0 . Davidson, for example, considers an event the proper cause of an effect; however, that effectiveness, that realisation, depends upon the existence of conditions, which are 
\f2\i not
\f1\i0  nonetheless the cause. Galton refers to enabling conditions of that effects, rather than proper causation.\
\
Galton identifies causation relationships between \ul events\ulnone  and \ul states\ulnone  (E1, S1), particularly 
\f2\i initiation
\f1\i0  and 
\f2\i termination
\f1\i0 , and a relationship between states and events (S1, E1), which is called 
\f2\i allows
\f1\i0 . For Galton, those relationships are not exactly causal, but rather \'93causal-like,\'94 as they often define the event itself. An example that explains this choice is the one taken from Kim (I believe originally from Lombard): a woman becomes a widow because her husband died, which is not really a causal relationship.\
\
Focussing now on \ul processes\ulnone , intended by Galton as open-ended (unbounded) homogeneous entities, similar to dynamic states (i.e. states of change). Both states and events happen at a time point, while events happen in an interval. Yet processes, differently from states, \ul can be causally efficacious\ulnone . The causal relationship between processes is called 
\f2\i perpetuates
\f1\i0 , as it continues a motion. It counterpart in states (S1, S2) is called 
\f2\i maintain
\f1\i0 . The two relationships of initiation and termination introduced before can also be applied between events and processes as the latter can act as \'93stative\'94 (in a DOLCE sense).\
\
To summarise a few discussed points:\
S= state\
E= event\
P= process\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
