\f1\i0 \cf0 CMC can also describe \ul negative causation\ulnone  (or absence causation), e.g. the absence of x caused y.\
\
Note that the paper assumes a more classic interpretation of endurant and perdurant (e.g. 
\f2\i a la
\f1\i0  DOLCE) that departs from Galton. E.g. perdurant, therefore, includes processes and events, and endurant participates in the perdurant. Processes can change and do not have temporal parts, while events have temporal parts and are \'93completed.\'94 States are also perdurant, defined as qualitative occurrents. Instead in Galton processes and events are endurant(continuant)-like.\
\
As a premise, the article pairs the notion of change and causation in a more explicit way than in Galton, i.e. if there is a change, something has cause it, and, due to its framing, that cause is \ul agentive\ulnone .\
\
