\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf0 Offers a UFO-based ontological analysis of prevention, i.e. blocking a phenomena (event) before occurs or interrupting it while it is ongoing. The work, being based on UFO, poses emphasis on the roles of dispositions (and their relation with events as manifestation of object\'92s dispositions). According with this framework, a situation, i.e. \'93[\'85] transformations from one piece of reality to another [\'85]\'94 
\f2\i activates
\f1\i0  a disposition, which is 
\f2\i manifested by
\f1\i0  an event in which the object that 
\f2\i bears
\f1\i0  the disposition participates. The event 
\f2\i brings about
\f1\i0  another situation (E1 triggers S1, in this case S stands for \'93situation\'94) and E1, E2, En 
\f2\i directly cause
\f1\i0  E3, Em in a causal chain configuration. \cf2 *although in the CRIMA ontology we do not have situation and disposition, this characterisation is useful to define that properties are attached to objects and that objects participate in causal mechanisms\cf0  \cf2 (situation activates disposition manifested in event)\cf0 . \cf2 Also note that in this representation are objects (endurants) that creates and terminates events.\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf4 To perform the analysis of prevention, thus dispositions that are not manifested, the paper delves into an extension of UFO for types and incompatibility defining also the Mutual Activation Partner relation between two dispositions. Regarding the incompatibility, this is defined when two situations are in conflict (only one can be obtained).\
\
Arriving to the notion of prevention, the intuition is that, if events are aggregates of dispositions, to block the happening of an event, it is necessary to modify the dispositions (including MAP). Thus to prevent the options could be: 1) to alter the dispositions bear by the objects, 2) to remove the object from the situation 3) to remove the disposition that is coupled in a MAP relations, 4) to introduce an incompatible disposition.\
\
Prevention can be indirect and direct, as in the case or causation. An example of direct prevention is the one of antidotes for poisons. Those type of preventions are called 
\f2\i \ul countermeasures
\f1\i0 \ulnone . Those countermeasure mechanisms can be designed following several strategies (see 1-4 points above).\cf2 *the concept of countermeasure probably fits well the one of mitigation/adaptation, and could be explored for \'93Mitigates.\'94 Yet, I am not totally convinced that this approach works with social entities, although it claims it can. The example provided in this regard (a theft in a building) is ultimately addressed in a physical form, such as installing locking material, rather in a proper social strategy.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
